European Stocks Extend Drop as S&P Revises U.S. Credit Outlook to Negative

-- B y   W i l l   H a d f i e l d
-- 
2011-04-18T13:08:14Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-18/european-stocks-u-s-futures-slide-as-banks-insurance-companies-retreat.html
European stocks extended their
declines as  Standard & Poor’s  revised its outlook for the U.S.
to negative from stable. U.S. futures extended their losses.  Alpha Bank SA and Societe Generale SA led a selloff in
banks, both dropping more than 4 percent. Salzgitter AG lost 4
percent after Goldman Sachs Group Inc. recommended investors
sell the German steelmaker. Synthes Inc. soared 7.6 percent
after the company confirmed it has held talks about a possible
takeover by Johnson & Johnson.  The Stoxx Europe 600 Index slid 1.4 percent to 273.85 at
2:07 p.m. in  London . The gauge last week dropped 1.4 percent
after Alcoa Inc. and Google Inc. kicked off the U.S. earnings
season with results that missed analysts’ estimates and the
 International Monetary Fund  cut its growth forecasts.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Will Hadfield at 
 whadfield@bloomberg.net  